00:00:22.350 --> 00:00:25.690
How do astronomers
measure distance?

00:00:25.690 --> 00:00:29.280
How are they able to measure
how far away a star is?

00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:29.840
Ah, right.

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:33.140
So it turns out that measuring
the distance to the star

00:00:33.140 --> 00:00:34.660
is an interesting problem.

00:00:34.660 --> 00:00:37.690
So astronomers have come up
with two different techniques

00:00:37.690 --> 00:00:41.370
to estimate how far away
any given star might be.

00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:43.870
Now, that first
technique involves

00:00:43.870 --> 00:00:45.750
triangulation, or parallax.

00:00:45.750 --> 00:00:48.060
So the Earth orbits
the sun, right?

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:48.560
Yeah.

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:50.450
Well, as it orbits
that sun, there's

00:00:50.450 --> 00:00:53.940
a diameter of orbit
about 186 million miles.

00:00:53.940 --> 00:00:56.970
So by looking at a start
one day and then, maybe,

00:00:56.970 --> 00:00:58.800
six months later,
looking at it again?

00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:00.960
Astronomers can see a
difference in the viewing

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:02.470
angle for that star.

00:01:02.470 --> 00:01:05.170
So with a little trigonometry--
which is, frankly,

00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:08.740
terrifying to me-- the different
angles yield the distance.

00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:10.120
So this technique
works for stars

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:13.790
that are about 400 light years
away from earth, or closer.

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:15.900
Now, there's no direct
method currently

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:17.480
available to
measure the distance

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:21.860
to stars that are further than
400 light years from Earth.

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:24.331
But there's an
approximation, right?

00:01:24.331 --> 00:01:24.830
Yes.

00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:26.200
And this is a pretty clever one.

00:01:26.200 --> 00:01:27.560
This is the second technique.

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:30.780
Astronomers can use
brightness to figure out

00:01:30.780 --> 00:01:31.750
a star's distance.

00:01:31.750 --> 00:01:33.520
So they do this
because it turns out

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:36.760
that a star's color spectrum
is a good indication

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:38.050
of its actual brightness.

00:01:38.050 --> 00:01:40.100
So like blue, white, et cetera.

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:42.370
The relationship between
color and brightness

00:01:42.370 --> 00:01:45.700
has been proven using the
several thousand stars that

00:01:45.700 --> 00:01:48.610
are close enough to Earth to
have their distance measured

00:01:48.610 --> 00:01:51.290
directly, that would be the
400 light years and closer.

00:01:51.290 --> 00:01:54.030
So astronomers can
look at a distant star,

00:01:54.030 --> 00:01:55.570
determine its color spectrum.

00:01:55.570 --> 00:01:57.550
And from the color,
then they can

00:01:57.550 --> 00:01:59.950
determine the star's
actual brightness.

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:02.160
By knowing the actual
brightness and comparing it

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:04.800
to the apparent brightness
seen from Earth-- that is,

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:07.670
by looking at how dim the
star has actually become

00:02:07.670 --> 00:02:09.539
once its light
reaches the earth,

00:02:09.539 --> 00:02:11.630
they can determine that
the distance of the star

00:02:11.630 --> 00:02:13.250
is whatever it happens to be.

