00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:24.570
that astronomers use, including
the astronomical unit.

00:02:24.570 --> 00:02:27.750
So the astronomical unit refers
to the distance between Earth

00:02:27.750 --> 00:02:29.300
and the sun, the
average distance.

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:33.050
It's about 149 million
kilometers or something.

00:02:33.050 --> 00:02:34.470
Then you've got the light-year.

00:02:34.470 --> 00:02:35.840
Yeah, what is a light-year?

00:02:35.840 --> 00:02:37.840
So, a light-year is
like a regular year

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:39.080
but with fewer calories.

00:02:39.080 --> 00:02:39.760
Heh.

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:41.330
Actually, of course,
the light year

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:43.500
is the distance that
light can travel

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:47.670
through the vacuum of space
within the span one Earth year.

00:02:47.670 --> 00:02:51.290
So that's pretty big,
because light's pretty fast?

00:02:51.290 --> 00:02:51.790
Yeah, yeah.

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:55.380
We're talking just under
10 trillion kilometers.

00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:57.050
That's a pretty long distance.

00:02:57.050 --> 00:02:59.430
But I've got something
that's even longer than that.

00:02:59.430 --> 00:03:01.610
And that is a parsec.

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:02.180
Hang on.

00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:04.120
Is this a Star Wars reference?

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:05.300
